Resides, his great contentiori is that Scripture alone is to be followed, and that both the Pope and the Fathers can mistake; so he is all the less scrupulous in explaining their words. If the explanation be unsatisfactory, they mistake, and that is all. — In the answer to the quotation of Grosseteste, we find a clue to his doctrine of the existence, at once figurative and real, of Christ's Body in the Host. After consecration‚ he says, we think Christ's Body present, the bread having become the sign of that presence. Time, the Universal, and the Sensible, have no actual and real esse, except in so far as the mind knows them3 and so it is of the esse of every sign, qua tale. And yet every sign, besides the real esse that it acquires on becoming a sign, has also an independent natural esse. Thus, the bread being the sign of Christ's Body is Christ⁷s Body in reality, according to Wyclif’s system3 while, at the same time it is mere bread from another point of view. Logically, I suppose that Wyclif would admit that a statue has two entitie33 the one, as being of stone, &c., shaped in a certain fashion, the other, as representing this or that person.
